constructors.name: URL
constructors.summary: The URL() constructor returns a newly created URL object representing the URL defined by the parameters.

safari.notes: In Safari 14 and earlier, calling the URL constructor with a base URL whose value is undefined causes Safari to throw a TypeError; see WebKit bug 216841.

safari_ios.notes: In Safari 14 and earlier, calling the URL constructor with a base URL whose value is undefined causes Safari to throw a TypeError; see WebKit bug 216841.

constructors.title: URL()

dom-url-hash.name: hash
dom-url-hash.summary: The hash property of the URL interface is a USVString containing a '#' followed by the fragment identifier of the URL.
dom-url-hash.title: URL.hash

dom-url-hash.name: hash
dom-url-hash.summary: The URLUtilsReadOnly.hash read-only property returns a DOMString containing a '#' followed by the fragment identifier of the URL. The hash is not percent encoded.

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 38, Firefox returned the hash percent encoded. This has been fixed to match the spec.

firefox_android.notes: Before Firefox 38, Firefox returned the hash percent encoded. This has been fixed to match the spec.

dom-url-hash.title: URLUtilsReadOnly.hash

dom-url-host.name: host
dom-url-host.summary: The host property of the URL interface is a USVString containing the host, that is the hostname, and then, if the port of the URL is nonempty, a ':', followed by the port of the URL.
dom-url-host.title: URL.host

dom-url-host.name: host
dom-url-host.summary: The URLUtilsReadOnly.host read-only property returns a DOMString containing the host, that is the hostname, a ':', and the port of the URL.
dom-url-host.title: URLUtilsReadOnly.host

dom-url-hostname.name: hostname
dom-url-hostname.summary: The hostname property of the URL interface is a USVString containing the domain name of the URL.
dom-url-hostname.title: URL.hostname

dom-url-hostname.name: hostname
dom-url-hostname.summary: The URLUtilsReadOnly.hostname read-only property returns a DOMString containing the domain of the URL.
dom-url-hostname.title: URLUtilsReadOnly.hostname

dom-url-href.name: href
dom-url-href.summary: The href property of the URL interface is a USVString containing the whole URL.
dom-url-href.title: URL.href

dom-url-href.name: href
dom-url-href.summary: The URLUtilsReadOnly.href read-only property is a stringifier that returns a DOMString containing the whole URL.
dom-url-href.title: URLUtilsReadOnly.href

dom-url-origin.name: origin
dom-url-origin.summary: The origin read-only property of the URL interface returns a USVString containing the Unicode serialization of the origin of the represented URL.

firefox.notes: Results for URL using the blob scheme incorrectly returned null.

firefox_android.notes: Results for URL using the blob scheme incorrectly returned null.

dom-url-origin.title: URL.origin

dom-url-origin.name: origin
dom-url-origin.summary: The URLUtilsReadOnly.origin read-only property is a DOMString containing the Unicode serialization of the origin of the represented URL, that is, for http and https, the scheme followed by '://', followed by the domain, followed by ':', followed by the port (the default port, 80 and 443 respectively, if explicitely specified). For URL using file: scheme, the value is browser dependant.
dom-url-origin.title: URLUtilsReadOnly.origin

dom-url-password.name: password
dom-url-password.summary: The password property of the URL interface is a USVString containing the password specified before the domain name.
dom-url-password.title: URL.password

dom-url-pathname.name: pathname
dom-url-pathname.summary: The pathname property of the URL interface is a USVString containing an initial '/' followed by the path of the URL not including the query string or fragment (or the empty string if there is no path).

firefox.notes: pathname and search returned the wrong values so that for a URL of http://z.com/x?a=true&b=false, pathname would return "/x?a=true&b=false" and search would return "", rather than "/x" and "?a=true&b=false" respectively.

firefox_android.notes: pathname and search returned the wrong values so that for a URL of http://z.com/x?a=true&b=false, pathname would return "/x?a=true&b=false" and search would return "", rather than "/x" and "?a=true&b=false" respectively.

dom-url-pathname.title: URL.pathname

dom-url-pathname.name: pathname
dom-url-pathname.summary: The URLUtilsReadOnly.pathname read-only property returns a USVString containing an initial '/' followed by the path of the URL, not including the query string or fragment.
dom-url-pathname.title: URLUtilsReadOnly.pathname

dom-url-port.name: port
dom-url-port.summary: The port property of the URL interface is a USVString containing the port number of the URL. If the URL does not contain an explicit port number, it will be set to ''.
dom-url-port.title: URL.port

dom-url-port.name: port
dom-url-port.summary: The URLUtilsReadOnly.port read-only property returns a DOMString containing the port number of the URL.
dom-url-port.title: URLUtilsReadOnly.port

dom-url-protocol.name: protocol
dom-url-protocol.summary: The protocol property of the URL interface is a USVString representing the protocol scheme of the URL, including the final ':'.
dom-url-protocol.title: URL.protocol

dom-url-protocol.name: protocol
dom-url-protocol.summary: The URLUtilsReadOnly.protocol read-only property returns a DOMString containing the protocol scheme of the URL, including the final ':'.
dom-url-protocol.title: URLUtilsReadOnly.protocol

dom-url-search.name: search
dom-url-search.summary: The search property of the URL interface is a search string, also called a query string, that is a USVString containing a '?' followed by the parameters of the URL.

firefox.notes: pathname and search returned the wrong values so that for a URL of http://z.com/x?a=true&b=false, pathname would return "/x?a=true&b=false" and search would return "", rather than "/x" and "?a=true&b=false" respectively.

firefox_android.notes: pathname and search returned the wrong values so that for a URL of http://z.com/x?a=true&b=false, pathname would return "/x?a=true&b=false" and search would return "", rather than "/x" and "?a=true&b=false" respectively.

dom-url-search.title: URL.search

dom-url-search.name: search
dom-url-search.summary: The URLUtilsReadOnly.search read-only property returns a DOMString containing a '?' followed by the parameters of the URL.
dom-url-search.title: URLUtilsReadOnly.search

dom-url-searchparams.name: searchParams
dom-url-searchparams.summary: The searchParams readonly property of the URL interface returns a URLSearchParams object allowing access to the GET decoded query arguments contained in the URL.
dom-url-searchparams.title: URL.searchParams

dom-url-tojson.name: toJSON
dom-url-tojson.summary: The toJSON() method of the URL interface returns a USVString containing a serialized version of the URL, although in practice it seems to have the same effect as URL.toString().
dom-url-tojson.title: URL.toJSON()

URL-stringification-behavior.name: toString
URL-stringification-behavior.summary: The URL.toString() stringifier method returns a USVString containing the whole URL. It is effectively a read-only version of URL.href.
URL-stringification-behavior.title: URL.toString()

dom-url-username.name: username
dom-url-username.summary: The username property of the URL interface is a USVString containing the username specified before the domain name.
dom-url-username.title: URL.username

api.name: URL
api.summary: The URL interface is used to parse, construct, normalize, and encode URLs. It works by providing properties which allow you to easily read and modify the components of a URL.

notes: Before version 57, Firefox had a bug whereby single quotes contained in URLs are escaped when accessed via URL APIs (see bug 1386683).
To use it from chrome code, JSM and Bootstrap scope, you have to import it with Cu.importGlobalProperties(['URL']);.
Before version 57, Firefox had a bug whereby single quotes contained in URLs are escaped when accessed via URL APIs (see bug 1386683).
To use it from chrome code, JSM and Bootstrap scope, you have to import it with Cu.importGlobalProperties(['URL']);.

nodejs.notes: Has to be imported from the URL module.

api.title: URL

dom-urlsearchparams-urlsearchparams.name: URLSearchParams
dom-urlsearchparams-urlsearchparams.summary: The URLSearchParams() constructor creates and returns a new URLSearchParams object.
dom-urlsearchparams-urlsearchparams.title: URLSearchParams()

dom-urlsearchparams-append.name: append
dom-urlsearchparams-append.summary: The append() method of the URLSearchParams interface appends a specified key/value pair as a new search parameter.
dom-urlsearchparams-append.title: URLSearchParams.append()

dom-urlsearchparams-delete.name: delete
dom-urlsearchparams-delete.summary: The delete() method of the URLSearchParams interface deletes the given search parameter and all its associated values, from the list of all search parameters.

safari.notes: Removing a non-existent query parameter doesn't remove ? from the URL. See bug 193022.

safari_ios.notes: Removing a non-existent query parameter doesn't remove ? from the URL. See bug 193022.

dom-urlsearchparams-delete.title: URLSearchParams.delete()

interface-urlsearchparams.name: entries
interface-urlsearchparams.summary: The entries() method of the URLSearchParams interface returns an iterator allowing iteration through all key/value pairs contained in this object. The key and value of each pair are USVString objects.
interface-urlsearchparams.title: URLSearchParams.entries()

interface-urlsearchparams.name: forEach
interface-urlsearchparams.summary: The forEach() method of the URLSearchParams interface allows iteration through all values contained in this object via a callback function.
interface-urlsearchparams.title: URLSearchParams.forEach()

interface-urlsearchparams.name: keys
interface-urlsearchparams.summary: The keys() method of the URLSearchParams interface returns an iterator allowing iteration through all keys contained in this object. The keys are USVString objects.
interface-urlsearchparams.title: URLSearchParams.keys()

interface-urlsearchparams.name: toString
interface-urlsearchparams.summary: The toString() method of the URLSearchParams interface returns a query string suitable for use in a URL.
interface-urlsearchparams.title: URLSearchParams.toString()

interface-urlsearchparams.name: values
interface-urlsearchparams.summary: The values() method of the URLsearchParams interface returns an iterator allowing iteration through all values contained in this object. The values are USVString objects.
interface-urlsearchparams.title: URLSearchParams.values()

dom-urlsearchparams-get.name: get
dom-urlsearchparams-get.summary: The get() method of the URLSearchParams interface returns the first value associated to the given search parameter.
dom-urlsearchparams-get.title: URLSearchParams.get()

dom-urlsearchparams-getall.name: getAll
dom-urlsearchparams-getall.summary: The getAll() method of the URLSearchParams interface returns all the values associated with a given search parameter as an array.
dom-urlsearchparams-getall.title: URLSearchParams.getAll()

dom-urlsearchparams-has.name: has
dom-urlsearchparams-has.summary: The has() method of the URLSearchParams interface returns a Boolean that indicates whether a parameter with the specified name exists.
dom-urlsearchparams-has.title: URLSearchParams.has()

dom-urlsearchparams-set.name: set
dom-urlsearchparams-set.summary: The set() method of the URLSearchParams interface sets the value associated with a given search parameter to the given value. If there were several matching values, this method deletes the others. If the search parameter doesn't exist, this method creates it.
dom-urlsearchparams-set.title: URLSearchParams.set()

dom-urlsearchparams-sort.name: sort
dom-urlsearchparams-sort.summary: The URLSearchParams.sort() method sorts all key/value pairs contained in this object in place and returns undefined. The sort order is according to unicode code points of the keys. This method uses a stable sorting algorithm (i.e. the relative order between key/value pairs with equal keys will be preserved).
dom-urlsearchparams-sort.title: URLSearchParams.sort()

urlsearchparams.name: URLSearchParams
urlsearchparams.summary: The URLSearchParams interface defines utility methods to work with the query string of a URL.

firefox.notes: Prior to version 57 single quotes in URLs were escaped (see bug 1386683).

firefox_android.notes: Prior to version 57 single quotes in URLs were escaped (see bug 1386683).

nodejs.notes: Only available implicitly or as import from the URL module.

urlsearchparams.title: URLSearchParams

urls.name: input-url
urls.summary: <input> elements of type url are used to let the user enter and edit a URL.
urls.title: <input type="url">
